# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-control-tower
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Public clouds are managed by cloud service providers, which operate the underlying infrastructure such as servers, storage, networking, and data center facilities.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Users may also opt to manage their public cloud services with a third-party cloud management tool.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Managing a private cloud requires software tools to help create a virtualized pool of compute resources, provide a self-service portal for end users and handle security, resource allocation, tracking and billing.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Management tools for private clouds tend to be service driven, as opposed to resource driven, because cloud environments are typically highly virtualized and organized in terms of portable workloads.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] In hybrid cloud environments, compute, network and storage resources must be managed across multiple domains, so a good management strategy should start by defining what needs to be managed, and where and how to do it.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Policies to help govern these domains should include configuration and installation of images, access control, and budgeting and reporting.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Access control often includes the use of Single sign-on (SSO), in which a user logs in once and gains access to all systems without being prompted to log in again at each of them.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Cloud management combines software and technologies in a design for managing cloud environments.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Software developers have responded to the management challenges of cloud computing with a variety of cloud management platforms and tools.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] These tools include native tools offered by public cloud providers as well as third-party tools designed to provide consistent functionality across multiple cloud providers.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Administrators must balance the competing requirements of efficient consistency across different cloud platforms with access to different native functionality within individual cloud platforms.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] The growing acceptance of public cloud and increased multicloud usage is driving the need for consistent cross-platform management.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Rapid adoption of cloud services is introducing a new set of management challenges for those technical professionals responsible for managing IT systems and services.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Cloud-management platforms and tools should have the ability to provide minimum functionality in the following categories.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Functionality can be both natively provided or orchestrated via third-party integration.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Organizations may group these criteria into key use cases including Cloud Brokerage, DevOps Automation, Governance, and Day-2 Life Cycle Operations.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] High-end cloud management tools should also have the ability to handle system failures automatically with capabilities such as self-monitoring, an explicit notification mechanism, and include failover and self-healing capabilities.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Legacy management infrastructures, which are based on the concept of dedicated system relationships and architecture constructs, are not well suited to cloud environments where instances are continually launched and decommissioned.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Instead, the dynamic nature of cloud computing requires monitoring and management tools that are adaptable, extensible and customizable.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Cloud computing presents a number of management challenges.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Companies using public clouds do not have ownership of the equipment hosting the cloud environment, and because the environment is not contained within their own networks, public cloud customers do not have full visibility or control.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Users of public cloud services must also integrate with an architecture defined by the cloud provider, using its specific parameters for working with cloud components.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Integration includes tying into the cloud APIs for configuring IP addresses, subnets, firewalls and data service functions for storage.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Because control of these functions is based on the cloud provider’s infrastructure and services, public cloud users must integrate with the cloud infrastructure management.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Capacity management is a challenge for both public and private cloud environments because end users have the ability to deploy applications using self-service portals.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Applications of all sizes may appear in the environment, consume an unpredictable amount of resources, then disappear at any time.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] A possible solution is profiling the applications impact on computational resources.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] As result, the performance models allow the prediction of how resource utilization changes according to application patterns.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Thus, resources can be dynamically scaled to meet the expected demand.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] This is critical to cloud providers that need to provision resources quickly to meet a growing demand by their applications.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Charge-back—or, pricing resource use on a granular basis—is a challenge for both public and private cloud environments.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Charge-back is a challenge for public cloud service providers because they must price their services competitively while still creating profit.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Users of public cloud services may find charge-back challenging because it is difficult for IT groups to assess actual resource costs on a granular basis due to overlapping resources within an organization that may be paid for by an individual business unit, such as electrical power.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] For private cloud operators, charge-back is fairly straightforward, but the challenge lies in guessing how to allocate resources as closely as possible to actual resource usage to achieve the greatest operational efficiency.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Hybrid cloud environments, which combine public and private cloud services, sometimes with traditional infrastructure elements, present their own set of management challenges.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] These include security concerns if sensitive data lands on public cloud servers, budget concerns around overuse of storage or bandwidth and proliferation of mismanaged images.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Managing the information flow in a hybrid cloud environment is also a significant challenge.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] On-premises clouds must share information with applications hosted off-premises by public cloud providers, and this information may change constantly.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Hybrid cloud environments also typically include a complex mix of policies, permissions and limits that must be managed consistently across both public and private clouds.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] CMPs provide a means for a cloud service customer to manage the deployment and operation of applications and associated datasets across multiple cloud service infrastructures, including both on-premises cloud infrastructure and public cloud service provider infrastructure.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] In other words, CMPs provide management capabilities for hybrid cloud and multi-cloud environments.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] A cloud management platform (CMP) provides broad cloud management functionality atop both public cloud provider platforms and private cloud platforms.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] CMPs manage cloud services and resources that are distributed across multiple cloud platforms.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] The value of CMPs stands in delivering the maximum level of consistency between platforms without compromising depth of functionality.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Unfortunately, the meaning of the term "cloud management platform" (CMP) has evolved over the past decade so that the precise meaning of this term is often unclear in discussions of management strategy.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] One vendor using this term may mean something completely different from another.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Selecting the right management approach for cloud services is therefore a complex task.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Providers and vendors can further confuse the evaluation by highlighting only their strengths and avoiding their weaknesses.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Furthermore, each provider and vendor focuses on solving different aspects of cloud management, making it difficult to compare solutions.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] A minimum viable CMP must be able to provide support for all technology stack layers and orchestrate capabilities across them (IaaS, PaaS, SaaS, etc.) It must include a cloud-agnostic tool to support portability/migration to and across hybrid clouds.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] An integration framework will take advantage of existing automation tools used internally and combine these with new CMP features.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] The ability to provide native container support across virtual technologies is a prerequisite, and CMPs are now either container ‘native’ (architected using containers) or being reengineered to support containers.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Along with standard OS deployments, a CMP’s blueprinting function will enable administrators to create and provide image-based solutions and customized configurations.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Integration with other IT assets and databases (CMDB) and role-based access control and governance are key.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] As a consolidated control plane for IT operations, one of the primary roles of a CMP is the integration of existing application lifecycle tools, hypervisors, and cloud platforms.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Given that charter, CMPs must integrate with internal and external systems to manage multi-cloud services.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] The ability to support both published APIs and provide for customization, if needed, is a critical capability.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Like any other brokerage firm, a Cloud Services Brokerage (CSB) manages cloud services for clients.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Gartner explains that CSBs play an intermediary role in the cloud computing management process.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Since there are many Datacenters hosting the provided applications, the role of a service broker becomes very important in choosing the most suitable data center to serve the received request.
[src:aws-control-tower/cloud-management] Cloud services brokerages consolidate cloud services from one or more sources and allow customers to access these services through one portal.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:aws-control-tower/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] COSO updated their standards accordingly.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As companies began efforts to comply with these regulations, the interconnectedness of governance, risk management, and compliance became clear.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] This created a market for training and software to bring these function together; for example, in 2002, Symbiant, a UK software development company, created the first GRC software that let teams work together online, combining risk registers, evaluations and audit tracking all in one system.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] The term "Governance, risk, and compliance" or "GRC" was published by Scott Mitchell, founder of the Open Compliance and Ethics Group (OCEG), in an academic paper in 2007.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Governance, risk, and compliance (GRC) are three related facets that aim to assure an organization reliably achieves objectives, addresses uncertainty and acts with integrity.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Governance, risk and compliance (GRC) is a discipline that aims to synchronize information and activity across governance, and compliance in order to operate more efficiently, enable effective information sharing, more effectively report activities and avoid wasteful overlaps.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] If not integrated and instead tackled in a traditional "silo" approach, most organizations must sustain unmanageable numbers of GRC-related requirements due to changes in technology, increasing data storage, market globalization and increased regulation.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Specific fields have developed GRC approaches; there is financial GRC (aka FinGRC), Legal GRC, and Operational GRC.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As companies have begun to adopt artificial intelligence to help run their businesses, the risks intrinsic to AI raise GRC challenges to the companies using AI products.
[src:aws-control-tower/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As of 2025, some companies were beginning to adopt AI tools to help them manage GRC.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Hosted applications: From the 1990s traditional application service providers (ASPs) hosted (then-existing) applications on behalf of their customers.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Depending on the limitation of the underlying application, ASPs were forced to host applications on separate machines (if multiple instances of the applications could not be executed in the same physical machine) or as separate processes.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a more mature architecture which enables a similar service with lower operational cost.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Web applications: Popular consumer-oriented web applications (such as Hotmail) developed with a single application instance serving all customers.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a natural evolution from this model, offering additional customization to groups of users within (say) the same client organization.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] In a multitenancy environment, multiple customers share the same application, running on the same operating system, on the same hardware, with the same data-storage mechanism.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] The distinction between the customers is achieved during application design, so that customers do not share or see each other's data.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] This contrasts with virtualization, where components are transformed so that each customer application appears to run on a separate virtual machine.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] This is attractive because redesigning an application for multitenancy can be costly, particularly for software vendors who also continue to offer an on-premises single-tenant version of their product and would otherwise have to maintain two distinct products.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] When applications are repackaged as virtual appliances, the same appliance image can be deployed in ISV-hosted, on-premises, or trusted-third-party locations, and migrated from one deployment site to another over time.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Multitenancy allows for cost savings over and above the basic economies of scale achievable from consolidating IT resources into a single operation.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] An application instance usually incurs a certain amount of memory and processing overhead which can be substantial when multiplied by many customers, especially if the customers are small.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Multitenancy reduces this overhead by spreading it over many customers.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Further cost savings may come from licensing costs of the underlying software (such as operating systems and database management systems).
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Put crudely, if you can run everything on a single software instance, you only have to buy one software license.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] In addition, development of multitenant systems is more complex, and security testing is more stringent because multiple customers' data is being commingled.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Because of the additional customization complexity and the need to maintain per-tenant metadata, multitenant applications require a larger development effort.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Considerations such as how tenant data is partitioned, how per-tenant schema extensions are stored, and how shared resources are isolated must be taken into account.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Multitenancy simplifies the release management process.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] In a traditional release management process, packages containing code and database changes are distributed to client desktop and/or server machines; in the single-instance case, this would be one server machine per customer.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] These packages then have to be installed on each individual machine.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] With the multitenant model, the package typically only needs to be installed on a single server.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] This greatly simplifies the release management process, and the scale is no longer dependent on the number of customers.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] At the same time, multitenancy increases the risks and impacts inherent in applying a new release version.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] As there is a single software instance serving multiple tenants, an update on this instance may cause downtime for all tenants even if the update is requested and useful for only one tenant.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Also, some bugs and issues resulted from applying the new release could manifest in other tenants' personalized view of the application.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Because of possible downtime, the moment of applying the release may be restricted depending on time usage schedule of more than one tenant.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] A central design decision in a multitenant application is how each tenant's data is isolated within shared storage.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] When tenants share compute, storage, or network resources, a single tenant generating disproportionate load can degrade performance for others, a condition known as the "noisy neighbor" problem.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Mitigations include per-tenant rate limiting, resource quotas, and isolating high-demand tenants onto dedicated resources.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] According to Marc Brooker, in a multi tenant architecture, unrelated and uncorrelated workloads should be grouped together.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] That's because mixing different workloads, with different needs and patterns, hide the patterns of each workload.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Grouping workloads reduces the peak-to-average ratio of the overall system; individual workloads can utilize more resources during peak times without significantly increasing the overall cost structure of the system and subsequently helps you to achieve more cost efficiency.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Note that multiple workloads from the same application, customer or industry, tend to behave as a single workload.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are typically required to provide a high degree of customization to support each target organization's needs.
[src:aws-control-tower/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are expected to provide adequate security, robustness and performance between multiple tenants which is provided by the layers below the application in case of multi-instance applications.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] In telecommunications, **provisioning** involves the process of preparing and equipping a network to allow it to provide new services to its users.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] In National Security/Emergency Preparedness telecommunications services, *"provisioning"* equates to *"initiation"* and includes altering the state of an existing priority service or capability.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The concept of **network provisioning** or **service mediation**, mostly used in the telecommunication industry, refers to the provisioning of the customer's services to the network elements, which are various equipment connected in that network communication system.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Generally in telephony provisioning this is accomplished with network management database table mappings.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] It requires the existence of networking equipment and depends on network planning and design.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] In a modern signal infrastructure employing information technology (IT) at all levels, there is no possible distinction between telecommunications services and "higher level" infrastructure.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Accordingly, provisioning configures any required systems, provides users with access to data and technology resources, and refers to all enterprise-level information-resource management involved.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] As its core, the provisioning process monitors access rights and privileges to ensure the security of an enterprise's resources and user privacy.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] As a secondary responsibility, it ensures compliance and minimizes the vulnerability of systems to penetration and abuse.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] As a tertiary responsibility, it tries to reduce the amount of custom configuration using boot image control and other methods that radically reduce the number of different configurations involved.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Discussion of provisioning often appears in the context of virtualization, orchestration, utility computing, cloud computing, and open-configuration concepts and projects.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Once provisioning has taken place, the process of SysOpping ensures the maintenance of services to the expected standards.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Provisioning thus refers only to the setup or startup part of the service operation, and SysOpping to the ongoing support.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The services which are assigned to the customer in the customer relationship management (CRM) have to be provisioned on the network element which is enabling the service and allows the customer to actually use the service.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The relation between a service configured in the CRM and a service on the network elements is not necessarily a one-to-one relationship; for example, services like Microsoft Media Server (mms://) can be enabled by more than one network element.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] During the provisioning, the service mediation device translates the service and the corresponding parameters of the service to one or more services/parameters on the network elements involved.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The algorithm used to translate a system service into network services is called **provisioning logic**.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Electronic invoice feeds from your carriers can be automatically downloaded directly into the core of the telecom expense management (TEM) software and it will immediately conduct an audit of each single line item charge all the way down to the User Support and Operations Center (USOC) level.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The provisioning software will capture each circuit number provided by all of your carriers and if billing occurs outside of the contracted rate an exception rule will trigger a red flag and notify the pre-established staff member to review the billing error.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Server provisioning is a set of actions to prepare a server with appropriate systems, data and software, and make it ready for network operation.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] By auditing the system, you ensure OVAL compliance with limit vulnerability, ensure compliance, or install patches.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] After these actions, you restart the system and load the new software.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] This makes the system ready for operation.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Typically an internet service provider (ISP) or network operations center will perform these tasks to a well-defined set of parameters, for example, a boot image that the organization has approved and which uses software it has license to.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Many instances of such a boot image create a virtual dedicated host.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] There are many software products available to automate the provisioning of servers, services and end-user devices.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Examples: BMC Bladelogic Server Automation, HP Server Automation, IBM Tivoli Provisioning Manager, Redhat Kickstart, xCAT, HP Insight CMU, etc.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Middleware and applications can be installed either when the operating system is installed or afterwards by using an Application Service Automation tool.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Further questions are addressed in academia such as when provisioning should be issued and how many servers are needed in multi-tier, or multi-service applications.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] In cloud computing, servers may be provisioned via a web user interface or an application programming interface (API).
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] One of the unique things about cloud computing is how rapidly and easily this can be done.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Monitoring software can be used to trigger automatic provisioning when existing resources become too heavily stressed.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] In short, server provisioning configures servers based on resource requirements.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The use of a hardware or software component (e.g. single/dual processor, RAM, HDD, RAID Controller, a number of LAN cards, applications, OS, etc.) depends on the functionality of the server, such as ISP, virtualization, NOS, or voice processing.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Server redundancy depends on the availability of servers in the organization.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Critical applications have less downtime when using cluster servers, RAID, or a mirroring system.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Service used by most larger-scale centers in part to avoid this.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Additional **resource provisioning** may be done per service.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] There are several software on the market for server provisioning such as Cobbler or HP Intelligent Provisioning.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] User provisioning refers to the creation, maintenance and deactivation of user objects and user attributes, as they exist in one or more systems, directories or applications, in response to automated or interactive business processes.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] User provisioning software may include one or more of the following processes: change propagation, self-service workflow, consolidated user administration, delegated user administration, and federated change control.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] User objects may represent employees, contractors, vendors, partners, customers or other recipients of a service.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Services may include electronic mail, inclusion in a published user directory, access to a database, access to a network or mainframe, etc.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] User provisioning is a type of identity management software, particularly useful within organizations, where users may be represented by multiple objects on multiple systems and multiple instances.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] On-demand self-service is described by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) as an essential characteristic of cloud computing.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The self-service nature of cloud computing lets end users obtain and remove cloud services―including applications, the infrastructure supporting the applications, and configuration― themselves without requiring the assistance of an IT staff member.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The automatic self-servicing may target different application goals and constraints (e.g. deadlines and cost), as well as handling different application architectures (e.g., bags-of-tasks and workflows).
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Cloud users can obtain cloud services through a cloud service catalog or a self-service portal.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Because business users can obtain and configure cloud services themselves, this means IT staff can be more productive and gives them more time to manage cloud infrastructures.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] One downside of cloud service provisioning is that it is not instantaneous.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user, but it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The VM startup time is dependent on factors, such as image size, VM type, data center location, and number of VMs.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Mobile subscriber provisioning refers to the setting up of new services, such as GPRS, MMS and Instant Messaging for an existing subscriber of a mobile phone network, and any gateways to standard Internet chat or mail services.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The network operator typically sends these settings to the subscriber's handset using SMS text services or HTML, and less commonly WAP, depending on what the mobile operating systems can accept.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] A general example of provisioning is with data services.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] A mobile user who is using his or her device for voice calling may wish to switch to data services in order to read emails or browse the Internet.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The mobile device's services are "provisioned" and thus the user is able to stay connected through push emails and other features of smartphone services.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Device management systems can benefit end-users by incorporating plug-and-play data services, supporting whatever device the end-user is using..
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Such a platform can automatically detect devices in the network, sending them settings for immediate and continued usability.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] The process is fully automated, keeping the history of used devices and sending settings only to subscriber devices which were not previously set.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] One method of managing mobile updates is to filter IMEI/IMSI pairs.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Some operators report activity of 50 over-the-air settings update files per second.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] This refers to delivering mobile content, such as mobile internet to a mobile phone, agnostic of the features of said device.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] These may include operating system type and versions, Java version, browser version, screen form factors, audio capabilities, language settings and many other characteristics.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] As of April 2006, an estimated 5,000 permutations were relevant.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Mobile content provisioning facilitates a common user experience, though delivered on widely different handsets.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] Provisioning devices involves delivering configuration data and policy settings to the mobile devices from a central point – Mobile device management system tools.
[src:aws-control-tower/provisioning-technology] When getting a customer online, the client system must be configured.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:aws-control-tower/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
